# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: notary-tuf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A **digital signature** is a mathematical scheme for verifying the authenticity of digital messages or documents.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A valid digital signature on a message gives a recipient confidence that the message came from a sender known to the recipient.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Digital signatures are a type of public-key cryptography, and are commonly used for software distribution, financial transactions, contract management software, and in other cases where it is important to detect forgery or tampering.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Digital signatures are often used to implement electronic signatures, which include any electronic data that carries the intent of a signature, but not all electronic signatures use digital signatures.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] *Security* (existential unforgeability under chosen-message attack, or EUF-CMA): It should be computationally infeasible to generate a valid signature for a party without knowing that party's private key.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Here 1*n* refers to a unary number in the formalism of computational complexity theory.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] where *A**S*(*sk*, · ) denotes that *A* has access to the oracle, *S*(*sk*, · ), *Q* denotes the set of the queries on *S* made by *A*, which knows the public key, *pk*, and the security parameter, *n*, and *x* ∉ *Q* denotes that the adversary may not directly query the string, *x*, on *S*.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In 1976, Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman first described the notion of a digital signature scheme, although they only conjectured that such schemes existed based on functions that are trapdoor one-way permutations.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Soon afterwards, Ronald Rivest, Adi Shamir, and Len Adleman invented the RSA algorithm, which could be used to produce primitive digital signatures (although only as a proof-of-concept – "plain" RSA signatures are not secure).
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The first widely marketed software package to offer digital signature was Lotus Notes 1.0, released in 1989, which used the RSA algorithm.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Other digital signature schemes were soon developed after RSA, the earliest being Lamport signatures, Merkle signatures (also known as "Merkle trees" or simply "Hash trees"), and Rabin signatures.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In 1988, Shafi Goldwasser, Silvio Micali, and Ronald Rivest became the first to rigorously define the security requirements of digital signature schemes.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] They described a hierarchy of attack models for signature schemes, and also presented the GMR signature scheme, the first that could be proved to prevent even an existential forgery against a chosen message attack, which is the currently accepted security definition for signature schemes.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The first such scheme which is not built on trapdoor functions but rather on a family of function with a much weaker required property of one-way permutation was presented by Moni Naor and Moti Yung.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] One digital signature scheme (of many) is based on RSA.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] To create signature keys, generate an RSA key pair containing a modulus, *N*, that is the product of two random secret distinct large primes, along with integers, *e* and *d*, such that *e* *d* ≡ 1 (mod *φ*(*N*)), where *φ* is Euler's totient function.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The signer's public key consists of *N* and *e*, and the signer's secret key contains *d*.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Used directly, this type of signature scheme is vulnerable to key-only existential forgery attack.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] To create a forgery, the attacker picks a random signature σ and uses the verification procedure to determine the message, *m*, corresponding to that signature.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In practice, however, this type of signature is not used directly, but rather, the message to be signed is first hashed to produce a short digest, that is then padded to larger width comparable to *N*, then signed with the reverse trapdoor function.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] This forgery attack, then, only produces the padded hash function output that corresponds to σ, but not a message that leads to that value, which does not lead to an attack.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In the random oracle model, hash-then-sign (an idealized version of that practice where hash and padding combined have close to *N* possible outputs), this form of signature is existentially unforgeable, even against a chosen-plaintext attack.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] There are several reasons to sign such a hash (or message digest) instead of the whole document.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The signature will be much shorter and thus save time since hashing is generally much faster than signing in practice.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A hash function can be used to convert an arbitrary input into the proper format.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Without the hash function, the text "to be signed" may have to be split (separated) in blocks small enough for the signature scheme to act on them directly.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] However, the receiver of the signed blocks is not able to recognize if all the blocks are present and in the appropriate order.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] As organizations move away from paper documents with ink signatures or authenticity stamps, digital signatures can provide added assurances of the evidence to provenance, identity, and status of an electronic document as well as acknowledging informed consent and approval by a signatory.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The United States Government Printing Office (GPO) publishes electronic versions of the budget, public and private laws, and congressional bills with digital signatures.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Universities including Penn State, University of Chicago, and Stanford are publishing electronic student transcripts with digital signatures.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A message may have letterhead or a handwritten signature identifying its sender, but letterheads and handwritten signatures can be copied and pasted onto forged messages.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Even legitimate messages may be modified in transit.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] With a digital signature scheme, the central office can arrange beforehand to have a public key on file whose private key is known only to the branch office.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The branch office can later sign a message and the central office can use the public key to verify the signed message was not a forgery before acting on it.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A forger who *doesn't* know the sender's private key can't sign a different message, or even change a single digit in an existing message without making the recipient's signature verification fail.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Non-repudiation, or more specifically non-repudiation of origin, is an important aspect of digital signatures.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] By this property, an entity that has signed some information cannot at a later time deny having signed it.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Similarly, access to the public key only does not enable a fraudulent party to fake a valid signature.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Note that these authentication, non-repudiation etc. properties rely on the secret key *not having been revoked* prior to its usage.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Public revocation of a key-pair is a required ability, else leaked secret keys would continue to implicate the claimed owner of the key-pair.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Checking revocation status requires an "online" check; e.g., checking a certificate revocation list or via the Online Certificate Status Protocol.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Very roughly this is analogous to a vendor who receives credit-cards first checking online with the credit-card issuer to find if a given card has been reported lost or stolen.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Of course, with stolen key pairs, the theft is often discovered only after the secret key's use, e.g., to sign a bogus certificate for espionage purpose.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In a *known message* attack, the attacker is given valid signatures for a variety of messages known by the attacker but not chosen by the attacker.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In an *adaptive chosen message* attack, the attacker first learns signatures on arbitrary messages of the attacker's choice.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A universal forgery attack results in the ability to forge signatures for any message.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A selective forgery attack results in a signature on a message of the adversary's choice.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] An existential forgery merely results in some valid message/signature pair not already known to the adversary.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The strongest notion of security, therefore, is security against existential forgery under an adaptive chosen message attack.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] All public key / private key cryptosystems depend entirely on keeping the private key secret.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A more secure alternative is to store the private key on a smart card.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Many smart cards are designed to be tamper-resistant (although some designs have been broken, notably by Ross Anderson and his students).
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In a typical digital signature implementation, the hash calculated from the document is sent to the smart card, whose CPU signs the hash using the stored private key of the user, and then returns the signed hash.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Typically, a user must activate their smart card by entering a personal identification number or PIN code (thus providing two-factor authentication).
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] It can be arranged that the private key never leaves the smart card, although this is not always implemented.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] If the smart card is stolen, the thief will still need the PIN code to generate a digital signature.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] This reduces the security of the scheme to that of the PIN system, although it still requires an attacker to possess the card.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] A mitigating factor is that private keys, if generated and stored on smart cards, are usually regarded as difficult to copy, and are assumed to exist in exactly one copy.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Thus, the loss of the smart card may be detected by the owner and the corresponding certificate can be immediately revoked.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Private keys that are protected by software only may be easier to copy, and such compromises are far more difficult to detect.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Entering a PIN code to activate the smart card commonly requires a numeric keypad.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Some card readers have their own numeric keypad.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] This is safer than using a card reader integrated into a PC, and then entering the PIN using that computer's keyboard.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Readers with a numeric keypad are meant to circumvent the eavesdropping threat where the computer might be running a keystroke logger, potentially compromising the PIN code.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Specialized card readers are also less vulnerable to tampering with their software or hardware and are often EAL3 certified.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Smart card design is an active field, and there are smart card schemes which are intended to avoid these particular problems, despite having few security proofs so far.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a digital signature and a written signature is that the user does not "see" what they sign.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The user application presents a hash code to be signed by the digital signing algorithm using the private key.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] An attacker who gains control of the user's PC can possibly replace the user application with a foreign substitute, in effect replacing the user's own communications with those of the attacker.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] This could allow a malicious application to trick a user into signing any document by displaying the user's original on-screen, but presenting the attacker's own documents to the signing application.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] To protect against this scenario, an authentication system can be set up between the user's application (word processor, email client, etc.) and the signing application.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The general idea is to provide some means for both the user application and signing application to verify each other's integrity.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] For example, the signing application may require all requests to come from digitally signed binaries.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] One of the main differences between a cloud based digital signature service and a locally provided one is risk.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Many risk averse companies, including governments, financial and medical institutions, and payment processors require more secure standards, like FIPS 140-2 level 3 and FIPS 201 certification, to ensure the signature is validated and secure.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Technically speaking, a digital signature applies to a string of bits, whereas humans and applications "believe" that they sign the semantic interpretation of those bits.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In order to be semantically interpreted, the bit string must be transformed into a form that is meaningful for humans and applications, and this is done through a combination of hardware and software based processes on a computer system.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The problem is that the semantic interpretation of bits can change as a function of the processes used to transform the bits into semantic content.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] It is relatively easy to change the interpretation of a digital document by implementing changes on the computer system where the document is being processed.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] From a semantic perspective this creates uncertainty about what exactly has been signed.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] WYSIWYS (What You See Is What You Sign) means that the semantic interpretation of a signed message cannot be changed.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In particular this also means that a message cannot contain hidden information that the signer is unaware of, and that can be revealed after the signature has been applied.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] WYSIWYS is a requirement for the validity of digital signatures, but this requirement is difficult to guarantee because of the increasing complexity of modern computer systems.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The term WYSIWYS was coined by Peter Landrock and Torben Pedersen to describe some of the principles in delivering secure and legally binding digital signatures for Pan-European projects.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Digital signatures cryptographically bind an electronic identity to an electronic document and the digital signature cannot be copied to another document.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Paper contracts sometimes have the ink signature block on the last page, and the previous pages may be replaced after a signature is applied.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Digital signatures can be applied to an entire document, such that the digital signature on the last page will indicate tampering if any data on any of the pages have been altered, but this can also be achieved by signing with ink and numbering all pages of the contract.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Quality implementations: An implementation of a good algorithm (or protocol) with mistake(s) will not work.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Users (and their software) must carry out the signature protocol properly.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The private key must remain private: If the private key becomes known to any other party, that party can produce *perfect* digital signatures of anything.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The public key owner must be verifiable: A public key associated with Bob actually came from Bob.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] This is commonly done using a public key infrastructure (PKI) and the public key↔user association is attested by the operator of the PKI (called a certificate authority).
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] For 'open' PKIs in which anyone can request such an attestation (universally embodied in a cryptographically protected public key certificate), the possibility of mistaken attestation is non-trivial.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Commercial PKI operators have suffered several publicly known problems.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Such mistakes could lead to falsely signed, and thus wrongly attributed, documents.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] 'Closed' PKI systems are more expensive, but less easily subverted in this way.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Only if all of these conditions are met will a digital signature actually be any evidence of who sent the message, and therefore of their assent to its contents.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Legal enactment cannot change this reality of the existing engineering possibilities, though some such have not reflected this actuality.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] The first appears to have been in Utah in the United States, followed closely by the states Massachusetts and California.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Other countries have also passed statutes or issued regulations in this area as well and the UN has had an active model law project for some time.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Adoption of technical standards for digital signatures have lagged behind much of the legislation, delaying a more or less unified engineering position on interoperability, algorithm choice, key lengths, and so on what the engineering is attempting to provide.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Some industries have established common interoperability standards for the use of digital signatures between members of the industry and with regulators.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] These include the Automotive Network Exchange for the automobile industry and the SAFE-BioPharma Association for the healthcare industry.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] In several countries, a digital signature has a status somewhat like that of a traditional pen and paper signature, as in the 1999 EU digital signature directive and 2014 EU follow-on legislation.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Generally, these provisions mean that anything digitally signed legally binds the signer of the document to the terms therein.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] For that reason, it is often thought best to use separate key pairs for encrypting and signing.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Using the encryption key pair, a person can engage in an encrypted conversation (e.g., regarding a real estate transaction), but the encryption does not legally sign every message he or she sends.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Only when both parties come to an agreement do they sign a contract with their signing keys, and only then are they legally bound by the terms of a specific document.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] After signing, the document can be sent over the encrypted link.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] If a signing key is lost or compromised, it can be revoked to mitigate any future transactions.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] If an encryption key is lost, a backup or key escrow should be utilized to continue viewing encrypted content.
[src:notary-tuf/digital-signature] Signing keys should never be backed up or escrowed unless the backup destination is securely encrypted.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Key management concerns keys at the user level, either between users or systems.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This is in contrast to key scheduling, which typically refers to the internal handling of keys within the operation of a cipher.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Successful key management is critical to the security of a cryptosystem.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Cryptographic systems may use different types of keys, with some systems using more than one.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] These may include symmetric keys or asymmetric keys.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] In a symmetric key algorithm the keys involved are identical for both encrypting and decrypting a message.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Keys must be chosen carefully, and distributed and stored securely.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Asymmetric keys, also known as public keys, in contrast are two distinct keys that are mathematically linked.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] They are typically used together to communicate.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Public key infrastructure (PKI), the implementation of public key cryptography, requires an organization to establish an infrastructure to create and manage public and private key pairs along with digital certificates.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The starting point in any certificate and private key management strategy is to create a comprehensive inventory of all certificates, their locations and responsible parties.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This is not a trivial matter because certificates from a variety of sources are deployed in a variety of locations by different individuals and teams - it's simply not possible to rely on a list from a single certificate authority.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Certificates that are not renewed and replaced before they expire can cause serious downtime and outages.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Once keys are inventoried, key management typically consists of three steps: exchange, storage and use.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Prior to any secured communication, users must set up the details of the cryptography.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] In some instances this may require exchanging identical keys (in the case of a symmetric key system).
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] In others it may require possessing the other party's public key.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] While public keys can be openly exchanged (their corresponding private key is kept secret), symmetric keys must be exchanged over a secure communication channel.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Formerly, exchange of such a key was extremely troublesome, and was greatly eased by access to secure channels such as a diplomatic bag.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Clear text exchange of symmetric keys would enable any interceptor to immediately learn the key, and any encrypted data.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The advance of public key cryptography in the 1970s has made the exchange of keys less troublesome.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Since the Diffie-Hellman key exchange protocol was published in 1975, it has become possible to exchange a key over an insecure communications channel, which has substantially reduced the risk of key disclosure during distribution.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] It is possible, using something akin to a book code, to include key indicators as clear text attached to an encrypted message.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The encryption technique used by Richard Sorge's code clerk was of this type, referring to a page in a statistical manual, though it was in fact a code.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The German Army Enigma symmetric encryption key was a mixed type early in its use; the key was a combination of secretly distributed key schedules and a user chosen session key component for each message.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] In more modern systems, such as OpenPGP compatible systems, a session key for a symmetric key algorithm is distributed encrypted by an asymmetric key algorithm.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This approach avoids even the necessity for using a key exchange protocol like Diffie-Hellman key exchange.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Another method of key exchange involves encapsulating one key within another.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Typically a master key is generated and exchanged using some secure method.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This method is usually cumbersome or expensive (breaking a master key into multiple parts and sending each with a trusted courier for example) and not suitable for use on a larger scale.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Once the master key has been securely exchanged, it can then be used to securely exchange subsequent keys with ease.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This technique is usually termed key wrap.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] A common technique uses block ciphers and cryptographic hash functions.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] A related method is to exchange a master key (sometimes termed a root key) and derive subsidiary keys as needed from that key and some other data (often referred to as diversification data).
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The most common use for this method is probably in smartcard-based cryptosystems, such as those found in banking cards.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The bank or credit network embeds their secret key into the card's secure key storage during card production at a secured production facility.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Then at the point of sale the card and card reader are both able to derive a common set of session keys based on the shared secret key and card-specific data (such as the card serial number).
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This method can also be used when keys must be related to each other (i.e., departmental keys are tied to divisional keys, and individual keys tied to departmental keys).
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] However, tying keys to each other in this way increases the damage which may result from a security breach as attackers will learn something about more than one key.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This reduces entropy, with regard to an attacker, for each key involved.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] A recent method uses an oblivious pseudorandom function to issue keys without the key management system ever being in a position to see the keys.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] However distributed, keys must be stored securely to maintain communications security.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Security is a big concern and hence there are various techniques in use to do so.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Likely the most common is that an encryption application manages keys for the user and depends on an access password to control use of the key.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Likewise, in the case of smartphone keyless access platforms, they keep all identifying door information off mobile phones and servers and encrypt all data, where just like low-tech keys, users give codes only to those they trust.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] In terms of regulation, there are few that address key storage in depth.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] "Some contain minimal guidance like 'don’t store keys with encrypted data' or suggest that 'keys should be kept securely.'" The notable exceptions to that are PCI DSS 3.2.1, NIST 800-53 and NIST 800–57.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] For optimal security, keys may be stored in a Hardware Security Module (HSM) or protected using technologies such as Trusted Execution Environment (TEE, e.g.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Intel SGX) or Multi-Party Computation (MPC).
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Additional alternatives include utilizing Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), virtual HSMs, aka "Poor Man's Hardware Security Modules" (pmHSM), or non-volatile Field-Programmable-Gate-Arrays (FPGA) with supporting System-on-Chip configurations.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] In order to verify the integrity of a key stored without compromising its actual value a KCV algorithm can be used.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The major issue is length of time a key is to be used, and therefore frequency of replacement.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Because it increases any attacker's required effort, keys should be frequently changed.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This also limits loss of information, as the number of stored encrypted messages which will become readable when a key is found will decrease as the frequency of key change increases.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Historically, symmetric keys have been used for long periods in situations in which key exchange was very difficult or only possible intermittently.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Ideally, the symmetric key should change with each message or interaction, so that only that message will become readable if the key is learned (*e.g.*, stolen, cryptanalyzed, or social engineered).
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Security: Vulnerability of keys from outside hackers, malicious insiders.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Availability: Ensuring data accessibility for authorized users.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Heterogeneity: Supporting multiple databases, applications and standards.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Governance: Defining policy-driven access control and protection for data.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Governance includes compliance with data protection requirements.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Key management compliance refers to the oversight, assurance, and capability of being able to demonstrate that keys are securely managed.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Compliance can be achieved with respect to national and international data protection standards and regulations, such as Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard, Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act, Sarbanes–Oxley Act, or General Data Protection Regulation.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] A *key management system* (KMS), also known as a *cryptographic key management system* (CKMS) or *enterprise key management system* (EKMS), is an integrated approach for generating, distributing and managing cryptographic keys for devices and applications.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] They may cover all aspects of security - from the secure generation of keys over the secure exchange of keys up to secure key handling and storage on the client.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Thus, a KMS includes the backend functionality for key generation, distribution, and replacement as well as the client functionality for injecting keys, storing and managing keys on devices.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Many specific applications have developed their own key management systems with home grown protocols.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] However, as systems become more interconnected keys need to be shared between those different systems.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] To facilitate this, key management standards have evolved to define the protocols used to manage and exchange cryptographic keys and related information.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] KMIP is an extensible key management protocol that has been developed by many organizations working within the OASIS standards body.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The first version was released in 2010, and it has been further developed by an active technical committee.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The protocol allows for the creation of keys and their distribution among disparate software systems that need to utilize them.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] It covers the full key life cycle of both symmetric and asymmetric keys in a variety of formats, the wrapping of keys, provisioning schemes, and cryptographic operations as well as meta data associated with the keys.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The protocol is backed by an extensive series of test cases, and interoperability testing is performed between compliant systems each year.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] A list of some 80 products that conform to the KMIP standard can be found on the OASIS website.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The security policy of a key management system provides the rules that are to be used to protect keys and metadata that the key management system supports.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] This protection covers the complete key life-cycle from the time the key becomes operational to its elimination.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] A public-key infrastructure is a type of key management system that uses hierarchical digital certificates to provide authentication, and public keys to provide encryption.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] PKIs are used in World Wide Web traffic, commonly in the form of SSL and TLS.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Group key management means managing the keys in a group communication.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Most of the group communications use multicast communication so that if the message is sent once by the sender, it will be received by all the users.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] The main problem in multicast group communication is its security.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] In order to improve the security, various keys are given to the users.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] Using the keys, the users can encrypt their messages and send them secretly.
[src:notary-tuf/key-management] IETF.org released RFC 4046, entitled Multicast Security (MSEC) Group Key Management Architecture, which discusses the challenges of group key management.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Public key algorithms are fundamental security primitives in modern cryptosystems, including applications and protocols that offer assurance of the confidentiality and authenticity of electronic communications and data storage.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] They underpin numerous Internet standards, such as Transport Layer Security (TLS), SSH, S/MIME, and PGP.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Compared to symmetric cryptography, public-key cryptography can be too slow for many purposes, so these protocols often combine symmetric cryptography with public-key cryptography in hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Before the mid-1970s, all cipher systems used symmetric key algorithms, in which the same cryptographic key is used with the underlying algorithm by both the sender and the recipient, who must both keep the key secret.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Of necessity, the key in every such system had to be exchanged between the communicating parties in some secure way prior to any use of the system – for instance, via a secure channel.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This requirement is never trivial and very rapidly becomes unmanageable as the number of participants increases, when secure channels are not available, or when (as is sensible cryptographic practice) keys are frequently changed.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In particular, if messages are meant to be secure from other users, a separate key is required for each possible pair of users.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] By contrast, in a public-key cryptosystem, the public keys can be disseminated widely and openly, and only the corresponding private keys need be kept secret.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] For example, a software publisher can create a signature key pair and include the public key in software installed on computers.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Later, the publisher can distribute an update to the software signed using the private key, and any computer receiving an update can confirm it is genuine by verifying the signature using the public key.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] As long as the software publisher keeps the private key secret, even if a forger can distribute malicious updates to computers, they cannot convince the computers that any malicious updates are genuine.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] For example, a journalist can publish the public key of an encryption key pair on a website so that sources can send secret messages to the news organization in ciphertext.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Only the journalist who knows the corresponding private key can decrypt the ciphertexts to obtain the sources' messages—an eavesdropper reading email on its way to the journalist cannot decrypt the ciphertexts.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] However, public-key encryption does not conceal metadata like what computer a source used to send a message, when they sent it, or how long it is.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Public-key encryption on its own also does not tell the recipient anything about who sent a message—it just conceals the content of the message.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Applications built on public-key cryptography include authenticating web servers with TLS, digital cash, password-authenticated key agreement, authenticating and concealing email content with OpenPGP or S/MIME, and time-stamping services and non-repudiation protocols.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] One important issue is confidence or proof that a particular public key is authentic, i.e., that it is correct and belongs to the person or entity claimed, and has not been tampered with or replaced by some (perhaps malicious) third party.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] A public key infrastructure (PKI), in which one or more third parties, known as certificate authorities, certify ownership of key pairs.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This implies that the PKI system (software, hardware, and management) can be trusted by all involved.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] A web of trust decentralizes authentication by using individual endorsements of links between a user and their public key.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] PGP uses this approach, in addition to lookup in the domain name system (DNS).
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] The DKIM system for digitally signing emails also uses this approach.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] PGP, SSH, and the SSL/TLS family of schemes use this procedure; they are thus called hybrid cryptosystems.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] As with all security-related systems, there are various potential weaknesses in public-key cryptography.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Aside from poor choice of an asymmetric key algorithm (there are few that are widely regarded as satisfactory) or too short a key length, the chief security risk is that the private key of a pair becomes known.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] All security of messages, authentication, etc., encrypted with this private key will then be lost.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This is commonly mitigated (such as in recent TLS schemes) by using Forward secrecy capable schemes that generate an ephemeral set of keys during the communication which must also be known for the communication to be compromised.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Additionally, with the advent of quantum computing, many asymmetric key algorithms are considered vulnerable to attacks, and new quantum-resistant schemes are being developed to overcome the problem.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Beyond algorithmic or key-length weaknesses, some studies have noted risks when private key control is delegated to third parties.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Research on Uruguay’s implementation of Public Key Infrastructure under Law 18.600 found that centralized key custody by Trust Service Providers (TSPs) may weaken the principle of private-key secrecy, increasing exposure to man-in-the-middle attacks and raising concerns about legal non-repudiation.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] All public key schemes are in theory susceptible to a "brute-force key search attack".
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] However, such an attack is impractical if the amount of computation needed to succeed – termed the "work factor" by Claude Shannon – is out of reach of all potential attackers.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In many cases, the work factor can be increased by simply choosing a longer key.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] But other algorithms may inherently have much lower work factors, making resistance to a brute-force attack (e.g., from longer keys) irrelevant.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Some special and specific algorithms have been developed to aid in attacking some public key encryption algorithms; both RSA and ElGamal encryption have known attacks that are much faster than the brute-force approach.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] None of these are sufficiently improved to be actually practical, however.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Major weaknesses have been found for several formerly promising asymmetric key algorithms.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] The "knapsack packing" algorithm was found to be insecure after the development of a new attack.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] As with all cryptographic functions, public-key implementations may be vulnerable to side-channel attacks that exploit information leakage to simplify the search for a secret key.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] These are often independent of the algorithm being used.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Research is underway to both discover, and to protect against, new attacks.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Another potential security vulnerability in using asymmetric keys is the possibility of a "man-in-the-middle" attack, in which the communication of public keys is intercepted by a third party (the "man in the middle") and then modified to provide different public keys instead.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Encrypted messages and responses must, in all instances, be intercepted, decrypted, and re-encrypted by the attacker using the correct public keys for the different communication segments so as to avoid suspicion.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] A communication is said to be insecure where data is transmitted in a manner that allows for interception (also called "sniffing").
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] These terms refer to reading the sender's private data in its entirety.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] A communication is particularly unsafe when interceptions can not be prevented or monitored by the sender.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] A man-in-the-middle attack can be difficult to implement due to the complexities of modern security protocols.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] However, the task becomes simpler when a sender is using insecure media such as public networks, the Internet, or wireless communication.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In these cases an attacker can compromise the communications infrastructure rather than the data itself.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] A hypothetical malicious staff member at an Internet service provider (ISP) might find a man-in-the-middle attack relatively straightforward.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Capturing the public key would only require searching for the key as it gets sent through the ISP's communications hardware; in properly implemented asymmetric key schemes, this is not a significant risk.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In some advanced man-in-the-middle attacks, one side of the communication will see the original data while the other will receive a malicious variant.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Asymmetric man-in-the-middle attacks can prevent users from realizing their connection is compromised.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This remains so even when one user's data is known to be compromised because the data appears fine to the other user.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This can lead to confusing disagreements between users such as "it must be on your end!" when neither user is at fault.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Hence, man-in-the-middle attacks are only fully preventable when the communications infrastructure is physically controlled by one or both parties; such as via a wired route inside the sender's own building.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In summation, public keys are easier to alter when the communications hardware used by a sender is controlled by an attacker.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] One approach to prevent such attacks involves the use of a public key infrastructure (PKI); a set of roles, policies, and procedures needed to create, manage, distribute, use, store and revoke digital certificates and manage public-key encryption.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Web browsers, for instance, are supplied with a long list of "self-signed identity certificates" from PKI providers – these are used to check the *bona fides* of the certificate authority and then, in a second step, the certificates of potential communicators.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who could subvert one of those certificate authorities into issuing a certificate for a bogus public key could then mount a "man-in-the-middle" attack as easily as if the certificate scheme were not used at all.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] An attacker who penetrates an authority's servers and obtains its store of certificates and keys (public and private) would be able to spoof, masquerade, decrypt, and forge transactions without limit, assuming that they were able to place themselves in the communication stream.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Despite its theoretical and potential problems, Public key infrastructure is widely used.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Examples include TLS and its predecessor SSL, which are commonly used to provide security for web browser transactions (for example, most websites utilize TLS for HTTPS).
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Aside from the resistance to attack of a particular key pair, the security of the certification hierarchy must be considered when deploying public key systems.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Some certificate authority – usually a purpose-built program running on a server computer – vouches for the identities assigned to specific private keys by producing a digital certificate.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Public key digital certificates are typically valid for several years at a time, so the associated private keys must be held securely over that time.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] When a private key used for certificate creation higher in the PKI server hierarchy is compromised, or accidentally disclosed, then a "man-in-the-middle attack" is possible, making any subordinate certificate wholly insecure.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Most of the available public-key encryption software does not conceal metadata in the message header, which might include the identities of the sender and recipient, the sending date, subject field, and the software they use etc.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Rather, only the body of the message is concealed and can only be decrypted with the private key of the intended recipient.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This means that a third party could construct quite a detailed model of participants in a communication network, along with the subjects being discussed, even if the message body itself is hidden.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] However, there has been a recent demonstration of messaging with encrypted headers, which obscures the identities of the sender and recipient, and significantly reduces the available metadata to a third party.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] The concept is based around an open repository containing separately encrypted metadata blocks and encrypted messages.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Only the intended recipient is able to decrypt the metadata block, and having done so they can identify and download their messages and decrypt them.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Such a messaging system is at present in an experimental phase and not yet deployed.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Scaling this method would reveal to the third party only the inbox server being used by the recipient and the timestamp of sending and receiving.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] The server could be shared by thousands of users, making social network modelling much more challenging.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] During the early history of cryptography, two parties would rely upon a key that they would exchange by means of a secure, but non-cryptographic, method such as a face-to-face meeting, or a trusted courier.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This key, which both parties must then keep absolutely secret, could then be used to exchange encrypted messages.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] A number of significant practical difficulties arise with this approach to distributing keys.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Here he described the relationship of one-way functions to cryptography, and went on to discuss specifically the factorization problem used to create a trapdoor function.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Ellis, a British cryptographer at the UK Government Communications Headquarters (GCHQ), conceived of the possibility of "non-secret encryption", (now called public key cryptography), but could see no way to implement it.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In 1973, his colleague Clifford Cocks implemented what has become known as the RSA encryption algorithm, giving a practical method of "non-secret encryption", and in 1974 another GCHQ mathematician and cryptographer, Malcolm J.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Williamson, developed what is now known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] The scheme was also passed to the US's National Security Agency.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Both organisations had a military focus and only limited computing power was available in any case; the potential of public key cryptography remained unrealised by either organization.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] These discoveries were not publicly acknowledged until the research was declassified by the British government in 1997.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In 1976, an asymmetric key cryptosystem was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman who, influenced by Ralph Merkle's work on public key distribution, disclosed a method of public key agreement.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This method of key exchange, which uses exponentiation in a finite field, came to be known as Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This was the first published practical method for establishing a shared secret-key over an authenticated (but not confidential) communications channel without using a prior shared secret.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Merkle's "public key-agreement technique" became known as Merkle's Puzzles, and was invented in 1974 and only published in 1978.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] This makes asymmetric encryption a rather new field in cryptography although cryptography itself dates back more than 2,000 years.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In 1977, a generalization of Cocks's scheme was independently invented by Ron Rivest, Adi Shamir and Leonard Adleman, all then at MIT.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] The latter authors published their work in 1978 in Martin Gardner's Scientific American column, and the algorithm came to be known as RSA, from their initials.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] RSA uses exponentiation modulo a product of two very large primes, to encrypt and decrypt, performing both public key encryption and public key digital signatures.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Its security is connected to the extreme difficulty of factoring large integers, a problem for which there is no known efficient general technique.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] A description of the algorithm was published in the Mathematical Games column in the August 1977 issue of Scientific American.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] Since the 1970s, a large number and variety of encryption, digital signature, key agreement, and other techniques have been developed, including the Rabin signature, ElGamal encryption, DSA and ECC.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] In addition to the algorithms developed within the open academic and standards communities, several countries have developed national public-key cryptography standards for use within their jurisdictions.
[src:notary-tuf/public-key-cryptography] These include SM2 and SM9 (China), GOST R 34.10-2012 (Russia), EC-KCDSA (South Korea), and DSTU 4145 (Ukraine).
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:notary-tuf/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.8.1, 1.9.0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.8, 1.81, 1.82.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added or for marketing purposes.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Version numbers are often used to identify copies of a software product and compare them against another copy in a collaborative version control system.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Within software development teams, version control is used to keep track of incrementally-different versions of information in order to be able to roll any changes back.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Modern computer software is often tracked using two different software versioning schemes: an internal version number, which may be incremented many times in a single day, and a release version, which typically changes far less often.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Historically, file numbers were especially used in public administration and corporations to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This practice was introduced to computer files for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX file system for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a standardized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy, which is particularly useful when using software libraries, frameworks, and command-line applications.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] File numbers were used especially in public administration, as well as companies, to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] For computer files this practice was introduced for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX filesystem for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Later lists of files including their versions were added, and dependencies amongst them.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Linux distributions like Debian, with its dpkg, early on created package management software which could resolve dependencies between their packages.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Debian's first try was that a package knew other packages which depended on it.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] From 1994 on this idea was inverted, so a package that knew the packages it needed.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] When installing a package, dependency resolution was used to automatically calculate the packages needed as well, and install them with the desired package.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] To facilitate upgrades, minimum package versions were introduced.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Thus the numbering scheme needed to tell which version was newer than the required one.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In sequence-based software versioning schemes, each software release is assigned a unique identifier that consists of one or more sequences of numbers or letters.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This is the extent of the commonality; schemes vary widely in areas such as the number of sequences, the attribution of meaning to individual sequences, and the means of incrementing the sequences.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In some schemes, sequence-based identifiers are used to convey the significance of changes between releases.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Semantic versioning (aka SemVer) is a widely adopted version scheme that encodes a version by a three-part version number (Major.Minor.Patch), an optional prerelease tag, and an optional build meta tag.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In this scheme, risk and functionality are the measures of significance.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Breaking changes are indicated by increasing the major number (high risk); new, non-breaking features increment the minor number (medium risk); and all other non-breaking changes increment the patch number (lowest risk).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The presence of a prerelease tag (-alpha, -beta) indicates substantial risk, as does a major number of zero (0.y.z), which is used to indicate a work-in-progress that may contain any level of potentially breaking changes (highest risk).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] As an example of inferring compatibility from a SemVer version, software which relies on version 2.1.5 of an API is compatible with version 2.2.3, but not necessarily with 3.2.4.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] A fourth number may also be used to denote the software build, as was the case for Adobe Flash.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Some companies also include the build date and letters and other characters, such as Lotus 1-2-3 Release 1a.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added, but are not enough to warrant incrementing a major version number; for example, Internet Explorer 5 from 5.1 to 5.5 or Adobe Photoshop 5 to 5.5.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] A different approach is to use the *major* and *minor* numbers along with an alphanumeric string denoting the release type, e.g.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] A software release train using this approach might look like 0.5, 0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9 → 1.0b1, 1.0b2 (with some fixes), 1.0b3 (with more fixes) → 1.0rc1 (if it is stable *enough*), 1.0rc2 (if more bugs are found) → 1.0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] It is a common practice in this scheme to lock out new features and breaking changes during the release candidate phases and, for some teams, even betas are locked down to bug fixes only, to ensure convergence on the target release.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Again, in these examples, the definition of what constitutes a "major" as opposed to a "minor" change is entirely subjective and up to the author, as is what defines a "build", or how a "revision" differs from a "minor" change.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] : The most recent interface number that the library implements.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] : The implementation number of the current interface.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] : The difference between the newest and oldest interfaces that the library implements.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] : others may use a different meaning or simply ignore it.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] A similar problem of relative change significance and versioning nomenclature exists in book publishing, where edition numbers or names can be chosen based on varying criteria.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In most proprietary software, the first released version of a software product has version 1.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Some projects use the major version number to indicate incompatible releases.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Two examples are Apache Portable Runtime (APR) and the FarCry CMS.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Often programmers write new software to be backward compatible.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] For example, IBM z/OS is designed to work properly with 3 consecutive major versions of the operating system running in the same sysplex.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This enables people who run a high availability computer cluster to keep most of the computers up and running while one machine at a time is shut down, upgraded, and restored to service.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Often packet headers and file format include a version number – sometimes the same as the version number of the software that wrote it; other times a "protocol version number" independent of the software version number.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The code to handle old deprecated protocols and file formats is often seen as cruft.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Software in the experimental stage (alpha or beta) often uses a zero in the first ("major") position of the sequence to designate its status.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] However, this scheme is only useful for the early stages, not for upcoming releases with established software where the version number has already progressed past 0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The two purely numeric forms remove the special logic required to handle the comparison of "alpha < beta < rc < no prefix" as found in semantic versioning, at the cost of clarity.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.7.0, 1.8.0, 1.8.1, 1.9.0, 1.10.0, 1.11.0, 1.11.1, 1.11.2, and so on.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.7, 1.8, 1.81, 1.82, 1.9, etc.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Decimal versions were common in the 1980s, for example with NetWare, DOS, and Microsoft Windows, but even in the 2000s have been for example used by Opera and Movable Type.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In the decimal scheme, 1.81 is the minor version following 1.8, while maintenance releases (i.e. bug fixes only) may be denoted with an alphabetic suffix, such as 1.81a or 1.81b.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The standard GNU version numbering scheme is major.minor.revision, but Emacs is a notable example using another scheme where the major number (1) was dropped and a *user site* revision was added which is always zero in original Emacs packages but increased by distributors.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Similarly, Debian package numbers are prefixed with an optional "epoch", which is used to allow the versioning scheme to be changed.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In some cases, developers may decide to reset the major version number.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This is sometimes used to denote a new development phase being released.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] For example, *Minecraft* Alpha ran from version 1.0.0 to 1.2.6, and when Beta was released, it reset the major version number and ran from 1.0 to 1.8.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Once the game was fully released, the major version number again reset to 1.0.0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Some projects use negative version numbers.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] One example is the SmartEiffel compiler which started from −1.0 and counted upwards to 0.0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] To ease sorting, some software packages represent each component of the *major.minor.release* scheme with a fixed width.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Perl represents its version numbers as a floating-point number; for example, Perl's 5.8.7 release can also be represented as 5.008007.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This allows a theoretical version of 5.8.10 to be represented as 5.008010.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Other software packages pack each segment into a fixed bit width; for example, on Microsoft Windows, version number 6.3.9600.16384 would be represented as hexadecimal 0x0006000325804000.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The floating-point scheme breaks down if any segment of the version number exceeds 999; a packed-binary scheme employing 16 bits apiece breaks down after 65535.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Between the 1.0 and the 2.6.x series, the Linux kernel used odd minor version numbers to denote development releases and even minor version numbers to denote stable releases.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] For example, Linux 2.3 was a development family of the second major design of the Linux kernel, and Linux 2.4 was the stable release family that Linux 2.3 matured into.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] After the minor version number in the Linux kernel is the release number, in ascending order; for example, Linux 2.4.0 → Linux 2.4.22.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Since the 2004 release of the 2.6 kernel, Linux no longer uses this system, and has a much shorter release cycle.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The same odd-even system is used by some other software with long release cycles, such as Node.js up to version 0.12 as well as WineHQ.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Many projects use a date-based versioning scheme called **Calendar Versioning** (aka **CalVer**).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Ubuntu is one example of a project using calendar versioning; Ubuntu 18.04, for example, was released in April 2018.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This has the advantage of being easily relatable to development schedules and support timelines.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Some video games also use date as versioning, for example the arcade game *Street Fighter EX*.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] At startup it displays the version number as a date plus a region code, for example *961219 ASIA*.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] When using dates in versioning, for instance, file names, it is common to use the ISO 8601 scheme *YYYY-MM-DD*, as this is easily string-sorted in increasing or decreasing order.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The Wine project formerly used a date versioning scheme, which used the year followed by the month followed by the day of the release; for example, "Wine 20040505".
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The earliest development builds of *Minecraft* had a similar version formatting, but instead used DDHHMM, for example rd-131655 was created on the 13th (of May 2009) at 16:21.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Microsoft Office build numbers are an encoded date: the first two digits indicate the number of months that have passed from the January of the year in which the project started (with each major Office release being a different project), while the last two digits indicate the day of that month.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] So 3419 is the 19th day of the 34th month after the month of January of the year the project started.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Other examples that identify versions by year include Adobe Illustrator 88 and WordPerfect Office 2003.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] When a year is used to denote version, it is generally for marketing purposes, and an actual version number also exists.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] For example, Windows 95 is internally versioned as MS-DOS 7.00 and Windows 4.00; likewise, Windows 2000 is internally versioned as NT 5.0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Some software producers use different schemes to denote releases of their software.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The Debian project uses a major/minor versioning scheme for releases of its operating system but uses code names from the movie *Toy Story* during development to refer to stable, unstable, and testing releases.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] BLAG Linux and GNU features very large version numbers: major releases have numbers such as 50000 and 60000, while minor releases increase the number by 1 (e.g.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Alpha and beta releases are given decimal version numbers slightly less than the major release number, such as 19999.00071 for alpha 1 of version 20000, and 29999.50000 for beta 2 of version 30000.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Urbit uses *Kelvin versioning* (named after the absolute Kelvin temperature scale): software versions start at a high number and count down to version 0, at which point the software is considered finished and no further modifications are made.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In conjunction with the various versioning schemes listed above, a system for denoting prerelease versions is generally used, as the program makes its way through the stages of the software release life cycle.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Programs that are in an early stage are often called "alpha" software, after the first letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] After they mature but are not yet ready for release, they may be called "beta" software, after the second letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Generally alpha software is tested by developers only, while beta software is distributed for community testing.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Some systems use numerical versions less than 1 (such as 0.9), to suggest their approach toward a final "1.0" release.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This is a common convention in open source software.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] However, if the prerelease version is for an existing software package (e.g. version 2.5), then an "a" or "alpha" may be appended to the version number.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] So the alpha version of the 2.5 release might be identified as 2.5a or 2.5.a.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Version numbers are used in practical terms by the consumer, or client, to identify or compare their copy of the software product against another copy, such as the newest version released by the developer.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] For the programmer or company, versioning is often used on a revision-by-revision basis, where individual parts of the software are compared and contrasted with newer or older revisions of those same parts, often in a collaborative version control system.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a formalized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The purpose of such policies is to make it easier for other programmers to know when code changes are likely to break things they have written.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Such policies are especially important for software libraries and frameworks, but may also be very useful for command-line applications (which may be called from other applications) and for other applications (which may be scripted and/or extended by third parties).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] A **software release train** is a form of software release schedule in which a number of distinct series of versioned software releases for multiple products are released as a number of different "trains" on a regular schedule.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Generally, for each product line, a number of different release trains are running at a given time, with each train moving from initial release to eventual maturity and retirement on a planned schedule.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Users may experiment with a newer release train before adopting it for production, allowing them to experiment with newer, "raw", releases early, while continuing to follow the previous train's point releases for their production systems prior to moving to the new release train as it becomes mature.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Cisco's IOS software platform used a release train schedule with many distinct trains for many years.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] More recently, a number of other platforms including Firefox and Fenix for Android, Eclipse, LibreOffice, Ubuntu, Fedora, Python, digiKam and VMware have adopted the release train model.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Software may have an "internal" version number which differs from the version number shown in the product name (and which typically follows version numbering rules more consistently).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Windows 10 was initially intended to be NT 6.4, as the earliest Technical Preview build shared to the public is numbered 6.4.9841.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] However, that did not last as the version of Windows 10 was quickly artificially increased to 10.0 to align with the commercial name, resulting in the first released version of the operating system being numbered 10.0.10240.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Note, however, that Windows NT is only on its fifth major revision, as its first release was numbered 3.1 (to match the then-current Windows release number) and the Windows 10 launching made a version leap from 6.3 to 10.0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] A relatively common practice is to make major jumps in version numbers for marketing reasons.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Sometimes software vendors just bypass the 1.0 release or quickly release a release with a subsequent version number because 1.0 software is considered by many customers too immature to trust with production deployments.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] For example, as in the case of dBase II, a product is launched with a version number that implies that it is more mature than it is.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Other times version numbers are increased to match those of competitors.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This can be seen in many examples of product version numbering by Microsoft, America Online, Sun Solaris, Java Virtual Machine, SCO Unix, WordPerfect.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Microsoft Access jumped from version 2.0 to version 7.0, to match the version number of Microsoft Word.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Another example of keeping up with competitors is when Slackware Linux jumped from version 4 to version 7 in 1999.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This approach, panned by many because it breaks the semantic significance of the sections of the version number, has been adopted by an increasing number of vendors including Mozilla (for Firefox) and Google (for Google Chrome).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Sun also dropped the first digit for Solaris, where Solaris 2.8 (or 2.9) is referred to as Solaris 8 (or 9) in marketing materials.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] A similar jump took place with the Asterisk open-source PBX construction kit in the early 2010s, whose project leads announced that the current version 1.8.x would soon be followed by version 10.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The free-software and open source communities tend to release software early and often.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Initial versions are numbers less than 1, with these 0.x version used to convey that the software is incomplete and not reliable enough for general release or usable in its current state.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Backward-incompatible changes are common with 0.x versions.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Version 1.0 is used as a major milestone, indicating that the software has at least all major features plus functions the developers wanted to get into that version, and is considered reliable enough for general release.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] A good example of this is the Linux kernel, which was first released as version 0.01 in 1991, and took until 1994 to reach version 1.0.0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The developers of the arcade game emulator MAME do not ever intend to release a version 1.0 of the program because there will always be more arcade games to emulate and thus the project can never be truly completed.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Accordingly, version 0.99 was followed by version 0.100.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The Python Software Foundation has published PEP 440 – Version Identification and Dependency Specification, outlining their own flexible scheme, that defines an epoch segment, a release segment, prerelease and post-release segments and a development release segment.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] TeX has an idiosyncratic version numbering system, an unusual feature invented by its developer Donald Knuth.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Since version 3.1, updates have been indicated by adding an extra digit at the end, so that the version number asymptotically approaches the number π, so 3.14 effectively means 3.2 in semantic versioning.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] (This is a form of unary numbering; the version number is the number of digits.) Since 2021, the version number has been 3.141592653.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This is a reflection of TeX being very stable, and only minor updates are anticipated.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] TeX developer Donald Knuth has stated that the *"absolutely final change (to be made after [his] death)"* will be to change the version number to π, at which point all remaining bugs will become permanent features.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In a similar way, the version number of Metafont asymptotically approaches Euler's number, e.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Metafont was also devised by Donald Knuth as a companion to his TeX typesetting system.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] During the era of the classic Mac OS, minor version numbers rarely went beyond ".1".
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] When they did, they usually jumped straight to ".5", suggesting the release was "more significant".
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Thus, "8.5" was marketed as its own release, representing "Mac OS 8 and a half", and 8.6 effectively meant "8.5.1".
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Mac OS X departed from this trend, in large part because "X" (the Roman numeral for 10) was in the name of the product.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] As a result, all versions of OS X began with the number 10.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The first major release of OS X was given the version number 10.0, but the next major release was not 11.0.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Instead, it was numbered 10.1, followed by 10.2, 10.3, and so on for each subsequent major release.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Thus the 11th major version of OS X was labeled "10.10".
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Even though the "X" was dropped from the name as of macOS 10.12, this numbering scheme continued through macOS 10.15.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Under the "X"-based versioning scheme, the third number (instead of the second) denoted a minor release, and additional updates below this level, as well as updates to a given major version of OS X coming after the release of a new major version, were titled Supplemental Updates.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The Roman numeral X was concurrently leveraged for marketing purposes across multiple product lines.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Both QuickTime and Final Cut Pro jumped from version 7 directly to version 10, QuickTime X and Final Cut Pro X.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Like Mac OS X itself, the products were not upgrades to previous versions, but brand-new programs.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] As with OS X, major releases for these programs incremented the second digit and minor releases were denoted using a third digit.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The "X" was dropped from Final Cut's name with the release of macOS 11.0 (see below), and QuickTime's branding became moot when the framework was deprecated in favor of AVFoundation in 2011 (the program for playing QuickTime video was only named QuickTime Player from the start).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Apple's next macOS release, provisionally numbered 10.16, was officially announced as macOS 11 at WWDC in June 2020, and released in November 2020.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The following macOS version, macOS Monterey, was released in October 2021 and bumped its major version number to 12.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In June 2025, Apple announced an unified versioning scheme, using the year next to the release date, similar to model years in vehicles.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The versions that were released in the fall of 2025 are iOS 26, macOS 26, iPadOS 26, tvOS 26, watchOS 26 and visionOS 26.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The Microsoft Windows operating system was first labelled with standard version numbers for Windows 1.01 through Windows 3.2.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] After this Microsoft excluded the version number from the product name.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] For Windows 95 (version 4.0), Windows 98 (4.10) and Windows 2000 (5.0), year of the release was included in the product title.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] After Windows 2000, Microsoft created the Windows Server family which continued the year-based style with a difference: For minor releases, Microsoft suffixed "R2" to the title, e.g., Windows Server 2008 R2 (version 6.1).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] This style had remained consistent to this date.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The client versions of Windows however did not adopt a consistent style.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] First, they received names with arbitrary alphanumeric suffixes as with Windows Me (4.90), Windows XP (5.1), and Windows Vista (6.0).
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Then, once again Microsoft adopted incremental numbers in the title, but this time, they were not versioning numbers; the version numbers of Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows 8.1 are respectively 6.1, 6.2 and 6.3.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] In Windows 10, the version number leaped to 10.0 and subsequent updates to the OS only incremented build number (which is date-based) and update build revision (UBR) number.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] The successor of Windows 10, Windows 11, was released on October 5, 2021.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Despite being named "11", the new Windows release did not bump its major version number to 11.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Instead, it stayed at the same version number of 10.0, used by Windows 10.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Some computer file systems, such as the OpenVMS Filesystem, also keep versions for files.
[src:notary-tuf/software-versioning] Technical drawing and CAD software files may also use some kind of primitive versioning number to keep track of changes.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] A software update, sometimes referred to as a patch, can add functionalities and address flaws in existing code.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Unfortunately, in delivering updates to neutralize flaws, these systems can unintentionally introduce vulnerabilities that, in turn, can be exploited by attackers.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] The design of TUF acknowledges that all software repositories will likely be compromised at some point, so any security strategy must be prepared for that scenario.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] TUF-enabled systems focus on limiting the impact of attacks and providing a mechanism for recovery.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] This strategy of “compromise-resilience” improves on existing methods based on keysigning by incorporating techniques, such as separation of signing duties and setting a threshold number of required signatures.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Dividing the responsibility for authenticating a file or image ensures no single hacker can compromise the system.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] It also helps to ensure that keys used to perform a sensitive action can be stored in a secure, offline manner.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Even if one party—or the repository itself—is compromised, the number of projects affected will be limited.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] TUF is designed with an explicit threat model that assumes attackers may compromise software updates in specific ways.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Documented attacks on software update systems can include rollback attacks, freeze attacks, mix-and-match attacks, and arbitrary software installation, among others.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] TUF mitigates these risks through mechanisms such as versioned metadata, expiration times, and role-based signing with threshold signatures.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] To date, the list of tech companies and organizations using TUF include Foundries.io, IBM, VMware, Digital Ocean, Microsoft, Google, Amazon, Leap, Kolide, Docker, and Cloudflare.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] The technology that evolved into TUF was first developed at the University of Washington in 2009 by Justin Samuel and Justin Cappos, and its principles were first discussed in a paper Samuel and Cappos coauthored with Nick Mathewson and Roger Dingledine, researchers from The Tor Project, Inc.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Since 2011, TUF has been based at New York University Tandon School of Engineering, where Cappos continues to work with a team of graduate students and programmers in the Secure Systems Lab to supervise its maturation, development and integration into production use across different communities.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] One of the more significant earlier adoptions of TUF in the open-source community was by Docker Content Trust, an implementation of the Notary project from Docker that deploys Linux containers.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Notary, which is built on TUF, can both certify the validity of the sources of Docker images, and encrypt the contents of those images.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Through Notary Content Trust, TUF also secures operations for Microsoft Azure.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Since 2017, both Notary and TUF have been hosted by the Linux Foundation under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Cappos remains with the project as consensus builder.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] In December 2019, TUF was awarded “graduate” status within the organization, signifying that it has completed a series of steps needed to move the project to the highest level of maturity in the CNCF.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] These steps included completing an independent third party security audit, adopting the CNCF Code of Conduct, and explicitly defining a project governance and committer process.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] TUF became both the first security project and the first project led by an academic researcher to graduate within CNCF.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Because it was designed for easy adaptation, versions of TUF have been created in a number of programming languages.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] It has been independently implemented in the Go language by Flynn, an open-source platform as a service (PaaS) for running applications in production.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Implementations of TUF have also been written in Haskell, Ruby and Rust.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] A Rust version called Tough was created by Amazon Web Services Labs for use with on-demand cloud computing platforms and APIs .
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] Google has also implemented a version of TUF to secure its open source operating system, Fuchsia.
[src:notary-tuf/the-update-framework] In 2017, an adaptation of this technology called Uptane, designed to protect computing units on automobiles, was named one of the top security inventions for 2017 by Popular Science.
